{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti 2.230** declares that the *ācārya* (teacher/guru), father, and mother—emphasized throughout the preceding verses as objects of supreme reverence and service—correspond to the **three worlds**, **three stages of life** (*āśramas*), **three Vedas**, and **three sacred fires** (*garhapatya*, *dakṣiṇāgni*, and *āhavanīya*, respectively).[^1]\n\nThis is part of a broader rule on filial and pedagogical piety: service to these three constitutes the highest austerity (*tapas*), and no other religious duty should be undertaken without their permission.[^2] Specifically, 2.231 identifies the father as the *garhapatya* fire (householder's fire), the mother as the *dakṣiṇāgni* (southern fire), and the guru as the *āhavanīya* fire (offering fire), making this triad the most venerable.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, ch. 2, [¶230](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-8f1205).\n[^2]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, ch. 2, [¶229](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-696df2).\n[^3]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, ch. 2, [¶231](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/02/translation/#p-3e3f4a).",
